description.narrative:
The Bêkou Trust fund for CAR was launched in July 2014 by the European Union (EU), France, Germany and the Netherlands, to support the country in the post conflict and reconstruction phase using a LRRD approach (Linking Relief, Rehabilitation and Development). Switzerland and Italy later joined the fund.   Under the Bêkou Fund, two Cordaid health projects (112059 and 113430) received funding worth approximately 7.3 m EURO in the period February 2015 to June 2018. This funding for “Support to the restoration of the health system in the Bangassou and Bossangoa Regions "enabled  three Health Districts (Bossangoa (Prefecture Ouham) in  Health Region 3 and Bangassou and Ouango (Prefecture Mbomou) in the Health Region 6) to recover with a final coverage of 53 health facilities serving an estimated population of 341,600 inhabitants. The project approach used Results Based Financing with targeted free healthcare (PLWs and <5) in accordance with the Ministry of Health Guidelines.
Internal and external evaluations and a counter verification  in 2016 and 2018 found good results despite several serious constraints and incidents, namely the looting of the Cordaid office of Bangui in September 2015 and the humanitarian crisis in Bangassou from May 2017, which saw the closure of the regional drug depot of Assomesca,  a local faith-based pharmaceutical NGO,  and in March 2018, the looting of the Cordaid sub-office (AAP) in Bangassou and a major theft of drugs.
 The main findings of the evaluation and counter verification are:
- the health system is operational again;
- the 25 health facilities in the Health District have been reopened, renovated and re-equipped,
- according to quarterly community satisfaction surveys, people are satisfied with the services provided;
- tracer drugs are available;
- free health care is provided to the target group;
- The health district management teams are re-equipped and operational.
Virtually all the quantity and quality indicators have improved
